ce:section.ce:para:
The relative standard deviation (RSD) percentage values were measured for five batches prepared under identical conditions to assess the reproducibility of the fluorometric probe for malachite green detection. The RSD values did not exceed 3.56 %, indicating excellent reproducibility and consistent performance of the probe across multiple batches. This supports the reliability of the probe for routine analysis. Additionally, the selectivity of the probe was rigorously tested by evaluating its response in the presence of 5.0 mM concentrations of various interfering ions, including K+, Na+, Li+, Ca2+, Mg2+, Ba2+, Al3+, Cu2+, Cl−, and CO3
                        2−, as well as 20-fold concentrations of common organic compounds such as glucose, glutathione, cysteine, lemon yellow, Congo red, sunset yellow, curcumin, tartrazine, crystal violet, ascorbic acid, uric acid, dopamine, and Sudan I (Fig. 5
                        ). Importantly, it was observed that malachite green caused the most significant quenching effect on the r-CDs, which confirms the probe’s high sensitivity to this target analyte. The remarkable selectivity of the fluorometric probe is primarily attributed to the presence of MIPs, which are designed to selectively adsorb and bind malachite green molecules. These MIPs play a crucial role in enhancing the quenching of r-CDs by preferentially interacting with malachite green over the other tested ions and organic compounds, ensuring that the probe responds primarily to the target molecule.
